                <strong style="color: var(--nix-text-bright); font-size: 13px; display: block; margin-bottom: 6px;"><i class="fa fa-flash" style="color: #ff9f43;"></i> 1. Zero-Overhead Bare-Metal Performance</strong>
                <span style="font-size: 11.5px; color: var(--nix-text-secondary); line-height: 1.5; display: block;">
                    Unlike Docker containers or virtual machines, Nix services run natively as standard processes directly on Unraid's host CPU. There are no virtualized network bridges, overlay filesystems, or container namespace layers, resulting in lower RAM usage, absolute bare-metal CPU throughput, and instantaneous startup times.
                </span>
            </div>
            
            <div style="background: var(--nix-bg-secondary); border: 1px solid var(--nix-border-primary); border-radius: 4px; padding: 14px;">
                <strong style="color: var(--nix-text-bright); font-size: 13px; display: block; margin-bottom: 6px;"><i class="fa fa-repeat" style="color: #ff9f43;"></i> 2. Persistence on a RAM-based OS</strong>
                <span style="font-size: 11.5px; color: var(--nix-text-secondary); line-height: 1.5; display: block;">
                    Unraid runs entirely from a RAM disk loaded from your USB flash drive during boot. Any manually installed packages or modified libraries in directories like <code>/usr/bin</code> or <code>/lib</code> are lost on reboot. Nix installs everything in <code>/nix/store</code> on a persistent array/cache pool, ensuring all packages, tools, and configurations survive reboots without modifying your Slackware system files.
                </span>
            </div>

            <div style="background: var(--nix-bg-secondary); border: 1px solid var(--nix-border-primary); border-radius: 4px; padding: 14px;">
                <strong style="color: var(--nix-text-bright); font-size: 13px; display: block; margin-bottom: 6px;"><i class="fa fa-tachometer" style="color: #ff9f43;"></i> 3. Direct Hardware Access</strong>
                <span style="font-size: 11.5px; color: var(--nix-text-secondary); line-height: 1.5; display: block;">
                    Because Nix processes run natively, they have direct access to host hardware—including Nvidia, Intel, and AMD GPU nodes (<code>/dev/dri</code>)—without requiring complex Docker passthrough configurations, runtime flags, or special container drivers.
                </span>
            </div>

