    <!-- How it works -->
    <div style="margin-bottom: 25px;">
        <h3 style="color: #00a1ff; margin-bottom: 10px;"><i class="fa fa-info-circle"></i> How Nix Works</h3>
        <p style="color: var(--nix-text-primary);">
            Nix is a unique package manager that treats package installations as mathematical functions. Unlike traditional package managers (like <code>apt</code> or <code>pacman</code>) which overwrite shared directories like <code>/usr/bin</code> or <code>/lib</code>, Nix stores all packages in isolation inside the <strong>Nix Store</strong> (<code>/nix/store</code>).
        </p>
        <ul style="color: var(--nix-text-secondary); padding-left: 20px; margin-top: 8px;">
            <li style="margin-bottom: 8px;"><strong>Immutable Packages:</strong> Every package directory in the Nix store is prefixed with a cryptographic hash of all its inputs (source code, dependencies, compiler options). This prevents conflicts and guarantees reproducibility.</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: 8px;"><strong>Jailed Sandboxing:</strong> Background services run inside isolated filesystem namespaces (chroot jails), limiting access to your raw host shares unless directories are explicitly mapped in the service configuration.</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: 8px;"><strong>Process Supervision:</strong> Services are managed in user-space by <code>process-compose</code>, a lightweight, non-systemd supervisor that handles startup ordering, process recovery, and resource tracking. The plugin ships its own <code>rc.nix-daemon</code> init script that supervises both the <code>nix-daemon</code> and the <code>process-compose</code> service supervisor.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="color: #00a1ff; margin-top: 18px; margin-bottom: 10px;"><i class="fa fa-medkit"></i> Diagnostics</h3>
        <p style="color: var(--nix-text-primary);">
            From the <strong>Logs</strong> tab, the <strong>Download Diagnostics</strong> button assembles <code>nix.cfg</code>, the active <code>process-compose.yml</code>, all supervisor and per-service log files, plus CPU, memory, and Nix version information into a single tarball at <code>/tmp/nix-diagnostics-&lt;id&gt;.tar.gz</code>. The temporary directory is created with <code>0700</code> permissions and the contents are rewritten to <code>0600</code> before packaging, so the bundle contains only owner-readable data. Attach the file when opening a GitHub issue to give maintainers everything needed to reproduce an issue.
        </p>

        <h3 style="color: #00a1ff; margin-top: 18px; margin-bottom: 10px;"><i class="fa fa-lock"></i> Security</h3>
        <p style="color: var(--nix-text-primary);">
            The WebGUI enforces CSRF tokens on every state-changing endpoint (settings, install, service start/stop, sync-templates, garbage collection, global rebuild) and rejects requests from any non-POST verb. The Rust helper single-quote-escapes every interpolated value before building shell commands, so a service name containing <code>$()</code>, backticks, or <code>;</code> cannot break out of the <code>sh -c</code> sandbox. File reads from <code>/boot/config/plugins/nix/metadata/</code> validate the service name against a strict character class, and bind-mount sources are symlink-checked before mounting. All user-controlled data rendered in the web UI is HTML-escaped at every interpolation site.
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Performance Tuning -->
    <div style="margin-bottom: 25px; background: var(--nix-bg-secondary); border: 1px solid var(--nix-accent); border-radius: 6px; padding: 18px;">
        <h3 style="color: #00a1ff; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 12px;"><i class="fa fa-bolt"></i> Performance & Health Guidelines</h3>
        <p style="color: var(--nix-text-primary); margin-bottom: 15px;">To ensure maximum storage health, high speeds, and optimal CPU load on your Unraid server, follow these best practices:</p>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 16px;">
            <div style="background: var(--nix-bg-tertiary); border: 1px solid var(--nix-border-primary); border-radius: 4px; padding: 12px;">
                <h4 style="margin: 0 0 6px 0; color: var(--nix-text-bright); font-size: 13px;"><i class="fa fa-hdd-o" style="color: #e67e22;"></i> 1. Store Location (Crucial)</h4>
                <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 11.5px; color: var(--nix-text-secondary); line-height: 1.5;">
                    Always configure your Nix Store on a fast <strong>SSD pool share</strong> (such as cache, nvme, or system shares). Do <strong>NOT</strong> store the Nix directories on your USB flash drive (<code>/boot</code>) as the high write frequency of package evaluations will wear out the flash storage and cause array lockups.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div style="background: var(--nix-bg-tertiary); border: 1px solid var(--nix-border-primary); border-radius: 4px; padding: 12px;">
                <h4 style="margin: 0 0 6px 0; color: var(--nix-text-bright); font-size: 13px;"><i class="fa fa-cloud-download" style="color: #2ecc71;"></i> 2. Prefer Cache Builds</h4>
                <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 11.5px; color: var(--nix-text-secondary); line-height: 1.5;">
                    Keep <strong>Allow Source Compilation</strong> set to <strong>No</strong> under System Settings. This forces Nix to strictly use pre-built binary caches (caches.nixos.org). This avoids compiling packages locally from source code, saving enormous CPU cycles and preventing long build wait times.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div style="background: var(--nix-bg-tertiary); border: 1px solid var(--nix-border-primary); border-radius: 4px; padding: 12px;">
                <h4 style="margin: 0 0 6px 0; color: var(--nix-text-bright); font-size: 13px;"><i class="fa fa-shield" style="color: #d946ef;"></i> 3. Sandbox Isolation</h4>
                <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 11.5px; color: var(--nix-text-secondary); line-height: 1.5;">
                    Keep <strong>Enable Storage Sandboxing</strong> active. When active, Nix background processes are strictly locked out of your disks except for your configured `appdata` directories or mapped paths, protecting user shares from accidental writes.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
